Population Simulation

Initial Values

These are the parameters to construct our copula with tail dependence for which we obtain our environmental noise.

  • n: 10^{4}
  • dim: 100
  • rho: 0.1
  • thresh_hi: 1
  • thresh_lo: 0.4

These are the values that we have when we simulate our population throughout time.

  • r: 1
  • numSimulations: 1
  • initPopSize: 500
  • carryingCapacity: 500
  • timeSteps: 10^{4}

This is if we set a seed for our program.

  • setseed: FALSE
  • seed: 10

This is where we obtain additional information we want to include in our document.

  • filename: testtext
  • fileext: .txt

Construction of a Tail Dependent Random Variable

Here we construct our copula with tail dependence with the newCopulaWithTailDependence function.

res<-newCopulaWithTailDependece(params$n,params$dim,params$rho,params$thresh_lo,params$thresh_hi)

The parameters that we pass into the function indicate that:

  • we sample from 10^{4} points from a copula
  • our copula has dimension 100
  • we use the value of 0.1 for rho where rho is the normal copula parameter for the region of the copula that is not tail dependent.
  • we have the values of 0.4 for thresh_lo and 1 for thresh_hi.

This means that our copula has left tail dependence in every dimension.

Transformation of our Random Variable and Construction of New Random Variables

We now transforms all of our marginals of our 100-dimensional copula with left tail dependence into normal marginals.

res<-qnorm(res)

We now calculate the covariance matrix for 100-variate normal random variable.

covMatrix <- matrix(data=rep(0,times=params$dim*params$dim),nrow=params$dim,byrow=TRUE)
for(i in 1:params$dim){
  for(j in 1:(params$dim)){
   covMatrix[i,j] <- cov(res[,i],res[,j])
  }
}

We sum all of the entries of our covariance matrix to obtain the variance of the sum of all random variable to have

varSumRetain <- sum(covMatrix)

We use this variance to find the rho parameter to construct a 100-variate normal copula that has the same value for the variance of the sum of the marginals as our tail dependent random variable

rho <- findNormalCopulaParam(params$dim, varSumRetain)
newNormalCop <- normalCopula(param = rho,dim =params$dim)
newNormCop <- rCopula(params$n, newNormalCop)

We new transform this normal copula into normal marginals.

newMultiNormMarg <- qnorm(newNormCop)

We now create our comonotonic random variable with dimension 100

com_mat <- matrix(data=replicate(n=params$dim,res[,1]),ncol=params$dim)

This is the empirical cumulative density function of three random variables. These three random variables are the sum of the 100 marginals of each the three cases. The variance of the sum of these random variables respectively are:

  • comonotonic: 9948.7084364
  • comonotonic in the tail: 7695.4088428
  • not comonotonic: 7650.0038448

Note that the variance for the comonotonic in the tail case and not comonotonic are similar. Also note that the variance for the comonotonic case is greater than the other two cases.

This is the ecdfplot of the sum of the marginals of each of the three random variables.

We have three random variables where each of them have 100 marginals. Each of these random variables represents the environmental noise on a population each with 100 metapopulations. We use a stochastic ricker model to model how the population fluctuates over time

ricker <-function(curpop,r,k,eps){
  return(curpop*exp(r*(1-(curpop/k))+eps))
}

upB <- max(quantile(avgPopSizeCom,0.98),quantile(avgPopSizeRes,0.98),quantile(avgPopSizeNewRes,0.98))

com <- data.frame(population =avgPopSizeCom[avgPopSizeCom<upB] )
res <- data.frame(population =avgPopSizeRes[avgPopSizeRes<upB] )
newRes <- data.frame(population =avgPopSizeNewRes[avgPopSizeNewRes<upB] )
com$type <- "com"
res$type <- "res"
newRes$type <- "newRes"

popfreq <- rbind(com,res,newRes)

ggplot(popfreq,aes(population,fill=type)) + geom_histogram(bins=200, alpha =0.6, position ='identity')

hist(avgPopSizeCom[avgPopSizeCom<upB],breaks=200)

print(paste0("mean: ", mean(avgPopSizeCom)," median: ", median(avgPopSizeCom)))
## [1] "mean: 503.353917604045 median: 266.174530176096"
hist(avgPopSizeRes[avgPopSizeRes<upB],breaks=200)

print(paste0("mean: ", mean(avgPopSizeRes)," median: ", median(avgPopSizeRes)))
## [1] "mean: 498.628428746829 median: 464.224300627313"
hist(avgPopSizeNewRes[avgPopSizeNewRes<upB],breaks=200)
